LONDON. Manchester United have agreed a fee with Benfica for central defender Victor Lindelof. The Portuguese club have confirmed United will pay 30.7m to sign the Sweden international, with a further 8.8m ( 10m) payable based on performance incentives. Lindelof is yet to agree personal terms, with his proposed move to Old Trafford also subject to a medical and international clearance. A United statement read: Manchester United is pleased to announce that it has reached agreement with Benfica for the transfer of Victor Lindelof, subject to a medical examination, international clearance and personal terms. A further announcement will be made once the transfer is complete. Sky Sports News revealed in May that Jose Mourinho was planning on signing a central defender this summer and had identified Lindelof, Michael Keane and Virgil van Dijk as his three main targets. Sky Sports.&nbsp;